In March, Merrick Garland set out to become a Supreme Court justice, but instead, nearly eight months later he has become the unofficial mascot of Washington dysfunction.

When he was nominated in the spring, just after the unexpected death of longtime conservative icon, Justice Antonin Scalia, Garland was given the royal judicial treatment: Democratic aligned groups anointed him with millions of dollars of positive ads in Washington and in key battleground states
